HIV, non-communicable diseases in eight fundamental points
GENEVA - Non-communicable diseases (NCDs), such as heart disease, stroke, cancer, diabetes, and chronic respiratory diseases, account for 70% of all deaths.
There is irrefutable evidence that the use of tobacco, a sedentary lifestyle, poor diet, and excessive alcohol consumption increase the risk of dying prematurely from non-communicable diseases.
Yet, despite a broad awareness of the risks, global obesity is generally not controlled, while tobacco and alcohol consumption continue to rise.
It was in this context that non-communicable disease alliance networks convened from December 9 to 11 at the second World Forum of the Non-Communicable Diseases Alliance in the United Arab Emirates.
In their search for solutions aimed at regulating the MNT, they should draw inspiration from the movement against AIDS.
People living with and affected by HIV continue to carry out interventions, and their unique form of mobilization has been essential to the progress made.
Although the battle is not over, AIDS activists know that they can win this battle.
Similarly, a movement of mobilization against the MNT can reverse this epidemic.
Yet in 2015, Richard Horton, editor-in-chief of The Lancet, described the MNT community as being in a state of «semi-comatose» waiting for «a shock to its mind.» He added: «But who will have the courage to administer it?»
We believe there are lessons to be learned from activists in the fight against AIDS.
As global attention focuses on preventing non-communicable diseases, those striving to control preventable diseases must draw inspiration from the ABC approach of HIV/AIDS organizations.
The first letter that the MNT community must consider is "A", as in activism.
Anyone over the age of 40 surely remembers the images of AIDS activists participating in "die-ins" during scientific meetings around the world.
In the United States, activists fighting AIDS took to the streets, even causing the headquarters of the Food and Drug Administration to close for a day in October 1988.
Globally, activists have put pressure on governments and pharmaceutical companies to make medicines more affordable.
This activism continues and should serve as a model for action on non-communicable diseases.
Next, the MNT Community must adopt a more ambitious approach to budgets — the "B" in the AIDS movement's strategy.
Civil society and grassroots activism can mobilize the initial energies, but organizing and maintaining a broad coalition requires money.
The movement fighting AIDS has been clear on this issue from the beginning and has pushed for resources to effectively support its awareness and empowerment activities.
« C » represents coalitions: the movements fighting against AIDS soon realized that progress comes only with multiple supporters.
Activists have established links between people living with HIV and those who have other concerns, such as women's rights, intellectual property rights, nutrition, and housing.
Coalitions and specialized campaigns work better when they bring together internal and external leaders from public authorities, in order to combine their perspectives and expertise.
The movement fighting AIDS also realized that a comprehensive response to the epidemic is essential for the spread of its support.
Thus, "D," the determining factor of success, was to "draw attention to the interconnectedness of the challenge."
For example, lobbying education leaders to keep girls in school longer has contributed to providing young people with the knowledge and power to make intelligent decisions about when and with whom to negotiate protected sexual relationships.
Similarly, links have been established between groups working on poverty, on gender equality, and on nutrition: as many factors that played a driving role in the HIV/AIDS crisis.
Nonetheless, MNT are not less isolated in their causality and are also subject to a multisectoral approach to prevention.
Engagement - "E" - was what helped the AIDS movement gain such great influence.
By strategically borrowing from the movement for the rights of people with disabilities, which advocated the slogan "Nothing about us without us," the AIDS activists demanded the inclusion of active organizations in charge of addressing the disease.
For example, UNAIDS remains the only UN agency with seats on its governing body intended for representatives of civil society.
This standard is so deeply embedded in the movement against AIDS that it would almost be unthinkable for an AIDS meeting to take place without representation from the community.
Prevention efforts must also develop compelling narratives, and "F" — framing the issue — is essential for the HIV community to gain political leaders' support.
In particular, access to treatments for AIDS was presented as an issue of economic justice.
Presenting the story in this way leads to a significant reduction in drug prices, to the extent that more than half of the people living with HIV in low- and middle-income countries are on treatment.
An equally important formulation of the issue for AIDS, a very relevant question for the MNT movement, is that of responsibility.
The AIDS community has worked hard to focus more on the lifestyle choices of individuals, rather than on assigning responsibility to the state for providing healthcare and eliminating legal discrimination.
In the debate on AIDS, gender — the "G" of our movement — has been a significant issue.
HIV was initially considered a "disease of gays," and gender identity was embedded from the beginning in the DNA of the AIDS activism movement.
The gender dimensions of these diseases are no less important: it is enough to examine how alcohol and tobacco are marketed to understand this.
Therefore, the genre must become a focus for the prevention of MNT.
Finally, "H" — human rights — are the foundation of the response to AIDS.
Campaigns have been launched against discrimination in the workplace, in schools, and in medical centers.
The strategic dispute ensured equality under the law.
The movement fighting AIDS refused to hold major conferences in countries with repressive laws against people living with HIV.
The MNT movement could adopt the same tactic, for example, by refusing to meet in countries that fail to limit the advertising of unhealthy foods to children.
We could continue listing the lessons learned from the fight against AIDS throughout the alphabet, but we believe it is appropriate to close this list with the letter "H," since human rights have provided the answer to AIDS and should provide the answer to non-communicable diseases.
Poverty, exclusion, as well as social and economic marginalization, put people at greater risk for HIV.
The same applies to MNT.
The first reaction to the AIDS epidemic was to ask: "Why don't these people make better choices?" The AIDS activism movement clearly stated that this question is not the right one.
Today, with 70% of the planet at risk of premature death due to preventable diseases, "these people" represent a large number of us.
The communities of MNT and AIDS can learn from each other.
We are a stronger movement when we unite our strengths.
The opinions expressed here do not necessarily reflect those of UNAIDS.
